main.text: Nice to meet you! I am Ruffle. I can help you reflect on the material.
What does the phrase ''form follows function'' mean in the context of cell biology? Provide an example to illustrate your answer.
IT means that something should be constructed in a manner that supports the functionality occurring inside of it.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

The phrase ''form follows function'' in cell biology means that the structure of cell components and organelles is directly related to their function. For instance, ribosomes, which are responsible for protein synthesis, are found in high numbers in cells that synthesize large amounts of protein, such as those in the pancreas that produce digestive enzymes. Here, the form (high number of ribosomes) follows the function (protein synthesis).
Describe the structure and function of ribosomes. How do they contribute to protein synthesis?

RIbosomes may group together in clusters or float freely on cytoplasma,  They are large protein and RNA completes, consisits of a large and small subunits.   They receive orders for protein synsthesis from the Nucleus.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Ribosomes are cellular structures responsible for protein synthesis. They are large protein and RNA complexes, each consisting of two subunits, large and small. Ribosomes receive their “orders” for protein synthesis from the nucleus where the DNA transcribes into messenger RNA (mRNA). The mRNA travels to the ribosomes, which translate the code provided by the sequence of the nitrogenous bases in the mRNA into a specific order of amino acids, the building blocks of proteins.
Explain the role of mitochondria in a cell. Why are they often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells?
They make adensonine triphosphate, ATP, an energy carrying molecule.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Mitochondria are often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells because they make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the cell’s main energy-carrying molecule. They are bean-shaped structures each with a double membrane. Cellular respiration, the process of making ATP using the chemical energy in glucose and other nutrients, occurs in mitochondria. This process uses oxygen and produces carbon dioxide as waste.
How does the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells relate to the principle of ''form follows function''?
Muscles require energy, and Mitochondria uses oxygen to create that energy, and discards of the waste by producing carbon dixoide.
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

The concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells is high because these cells need considerable energy to keep the body moving. Mitochondria produce ATP, the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. This is an example of ''form follows function'' as the high concentration of mitochondria (form) is directly related to the high energy requirement of muscle cells (function).
What are peroxisomes and what functions do they perform in a cell? How do they contribute to the detoxification process in the body?
Small round organelles enclosed by a single membrane.  They break down fatty acids and amino acids, providing oxidation.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Peroxisomes are small, round organelles enclosed by single membranes that carry out oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. Many of these oxidation reactions release hydrogen peroxide, which would be damaging to cells; however, when these reactions are confined to peroxisomes, enzymes safely break down the hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water. For example, peroxisomes in liver cells detoxify alcohol.

What does the phrase ''form follows function'' mean in the context of cell biology? Provide an example to illustrate your answer.
define organelles
Sorry, that's not quite right. You might want to refer to the lesson or our model solution:

The phrase ''form follows function'' in cell biology means that the structure of cell components and organelles is directly related to their function. For instance, ribosomes, which are responsible for protein synthesis, are found in high numbers in cells that synthesize large amounts of protein, such as those in the pancreas that produce digestive enzymes. Here, the form (high number of ribosomes) follows the function (protein synthesis).
Describe the structure and function of ribosomes. How do they contribute to protein synthesis?
They receive orders for protein synthesis from the nucleus. They can be grouped together or be found individually.
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

Ribosomes are cellular structures responsible for protein synthesis. They are large protein and RNA complexes, each consisting of two subunits, large and small. Ribosomes receive their “orders” for protein synthesis from the nucleus where the DNA transcribes into messenger RNA (mRNA). The mRNA travels to the ribosomes, which translate the code provided by the sequence of the nitrogenous bases in the mRNA into a specific order of amino acids, the building blocks of proteins.
Explain the role of mitochondria in a cell. Why are they often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells?
they make the cell's main energy-carrying molecule.
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

Mitochondria are often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells because they make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the cell’s main energy-carrying molecule. They are bean-shaped structures each with a double membrane. Cellular respiration, the process of making ATP using the chemical energy in glucose and other nutrients, occurs in mitochondria. This process uses oxygen and produces carbon dioxide as waste.
How does the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells relate to the principle of ''form follows function''?
Muscle cells require a lot of energy to function so they require a high concentration of mitochondria.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

The concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells is high because these cells need considerable energy to keep the body moving. Mitochondria produce ATP, the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. This is an example of ''form follows function'' as the high concentration of mitochondria (form) is directly related to the high energy requirement of muscle cells (function).
What are peroxisomes and what functions do they perform in a cell? How do they contribute to the detoxification process in the body?

They are small, round organelles enclosed by single membranes. They carry out oxidation reactions that break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. The enzymes they produce break down harmful toxins.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Peroxisomes are small, round organelles enclosed by single membranes that carry out oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. Many of these oxidation reactions release hydrogen peroxide, which would be damaging to cells; however, when these reactions are confined to peroxisomes, enzymes safely break down the hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water. For example, peroxisomes in liver cells detoxify alcohol.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, if I understand correctly, the way a cell or its parts are shaped and structured is directly linked to what they do or their purpose.
Student (to the teacher): Could you perhaps provide an example to illustrate this concept?
Teacher (to the student): Ribosomes, structures responsible for protein synthesis, are found in large numbers in eukaryotic cells that synthesize large amounts of protein.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for the example! So, ribosomes, which are responsible for protein synthesis, are present in large numbers in cells that need to produce a lot of protein. This is a great illustration of how form follows function.
Student (to the teacher): Could you tell me more about the structure and function of these ribosomes?
Teacher (to the student): Ribosomes are cellular structures that synthesize protein. They can be found singularly or in groups known as polyribosomes.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for the information! So, ribosomes, which can be found either alone or in groups called polyribosomes, are responsible for making proteins.
Student (to the teacher): I'm curious, what are these ribosomes made of?
Teacher (to the student): Ribosomes are made of protein and RNA.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your answer! So, ribosomes are composed of protein and RNA.
Student (to the teacher): How do these ribosomes know what kind of protein to synthesize?
Teacher (to the student): Ribosomes receive instructions from the cell's nucleus.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, the nucleus of the cell gives orders to the ribosomes about which proteins to synthesize.
Student (to the teacher): How does the information from the nucleus reach the ribosomes?
Teacher (to the student): Cellular DNA is transcribed into messenger RNA. The mRNA is sent from the nucleus to the ribosomes, which translate it into amino acids.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your detailed explanation! So, the DNA in the nucleus is transcribed into messenger RNA (mRNA), which then travels to the ribosomes. The ribosomes then translate the mRNA into amino acids to synthesize proteins.
Student (to the teacher): Now, could we move on to the next topic? I'm curious about the role of mitochondria in cells. Could you explain that to me?
Teacher (to the student): Mitochondria provide energy for a cell to use.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your answer! So, mitochondria are the parts of the cell that provide energy.
Student (to the teacher): How do mitochondria produce this energy?
Teacher (to the student): Mitochondria use oxygen to produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the main energy-carrying molecule for the cell.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, mitochondria use oxygen to produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which is the main molecule that carries energy in the cell.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how mitochondria use oxygen to produce ATP?
Teacher (to the student): Using glucose and other nutrients, mitochondria create ATP through a process known as cellular respiration.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your answer! So, mitochondria use glucose and other nutrients to create ATP through a process called cellular respiration.

Student (to the teacher): Now, I'm curious about how the principle of "form follows function" applies to mitochondria. Could you explain how the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells relates to this principle?
Teacher (to the student): Mitochondria provide energy for cells to use, so it makes sense that muscle cells will have lots of them.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, because mitochondria provide energy for cells, muscle cells, which require a lot of energy, have a high concentration of mitochondria. This is another example of how form follows function.
Student (to the teacher): Now, could we move on to the next topic? I'm interested in learning about peroxisomes. Could you explain what they are and what functions they perform in cells?
Teacher (to the student): Peroxisomes break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also help remove toxins from your body.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your answer! So, peroxisomes are involved in breaking down fatty acids and amino acids, and they also help in detoxifying the body.
Student (to the teacher): How do peroxisomes carry out these oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids?
Teacher (to the student): Peroxisomes carry out these functions through oxidation reactions.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, peroxisomes use oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how peroxisomes contribute to the detoxification process in the body?
Teacher (to the student): An example would be peroxisomes in liver cells. They help break down alcohol.
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for the example! So, peroxisomes, like those in liver cells, help in breaking down substances like alcohol, contributing to the detoxification process.
Student (to the teacher): I'm curious, how do peroxisomes handle potentially harmful substances like hydrogen peroxide?
Teacher (to the student): Peroxisomes are enclosed by a single membrane. This helps keep harmful substances contained.

What does the phrase ''form follows function'' mean in the context of cell biology? Provide an example to illustrate your answer.
ribosomes are found in high numbers in eukaryotic cells that synthesize large amounts of protein
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

The phrase ''form follows function'' in cell biology means that the structure of cell components and organelles is directly related to their function. For instance, ribosomes, which are responsible for protein synthesis, are found in high numbers in cells that synthesize large amounts of protein, such as those in the pancreas that produce digestive enzymes. Here, the form (high number of ribosomes) follows the function (protein synthesis).
Describe the structure and function of ribosomes. How do they contribute to protein synthesis?
they synthesize protein
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

Ribosomes are cellular structures responsible for protein synthesis. They are large protein and RNA complexes, each consisting of two subunits, large and small. Ribosomes receive their “orders” for protein synthesis from the nucleus where the DNA transcribes into messenger RNA (mRNA). The mRNA travels to the ribosomes, which translate the code provided by the sequence of the nitrogenous bases in the mRNA into a specific order of amino acids, the building blocks of proteins.
Explain the role of mitochondria in a cell. Why are they often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells?
they make ATP
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

Mitochondria are often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells because they make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the cell’s main energy-carrying molecule. They are bean-shaped structures each with a double membrane. Cellular respiration, the process of making ATP using the chemical energy in glucose and other nutrients, occurs in mitochondria. This process uses oxygen and produces carbon dioxide as waste.
How does the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells relate to the principle of ''form follows function''?
they have a high concentration that produce ATP
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

The concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells is high because these cells need considerable energy to keep the body moving. Mitochondria produce ATP, the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. This is an example of ''form follows function'' as the high concentration of mitochondria (form) is directly related to the high energy requirement of muscle cells (function).
What are peroxisomes and what functions do they perform in a cell? How do they contribute to the detoxification process in the body?
they are small organelles enclosed by single membranes. they carry out oxidation reactions that break down fatty and amino acids
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Peroxisomes are small, round organelles enclosed by single membranes that carry out oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. Many of these oxidation reactions release hydrogen peroxide, which would be damaging to cells; however, when these reactions are confined to peroxisomes, enzymes safely break down the hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water. For example, peroxisomes in liver cells detoxify alcohol.

The principle of form follows function means that the function of a particular structure is specifically designed to help the structure carry out its particular function. These include:  (A)	Cells that need to make a lot of proteins, like pancreatic cells that make a high quantity of digestive enzymes, contain many ribosomes, the structure responsible for protein synthesis.  (B) Muscle cells have a very high concentration of mitochondria in order to make high amounts of ATP (the cell’s short-term stored energy) to keep your body moving.

can you tell me
Sorry, that's not quite right. You might want to refer to the lesson or our model solution:

Each ribosome is composed of two subunits, a large and a small, each of which contains both proteins and RNA. Ribosomes may group as clusters or remain individual ribosomes that freely float in the cytoplasm. Additionally, ribosomes may also attach to the cytoplasmic side of the endoplasmic reticulum or the nuclear envelope’s outer membrane. They are used for linking amino acids together in a particular order to make proteins, using the information within mRNA (which is made using DNA in the nucleus) to direct the identity and order of amino acids in the protein.

main.text: Teacher (to the student): Good morning, Riley! I would love to explain what 'form follows function' means. It basically means that everything has its place to work within a system. For example, ribosomes are found in high numbers in eukaryotic cells that synthesize

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, if I understand correctly, "form follows function" means that the structure of a cell or its components is designed in a way that allows it to perform its function effectively. For instance, the presence of many ribosomes in cells that synthesize large amounts of protein.
Student (to the teacher): Could you tell me more about the structure and function of these ribosomes?

Teacher (to the student): Sure! they are typically grouped together in clusters, called polyribosomes, with some individual ribosomes floating freely in the cytoplasm. They receive their 'orders' for protein synthesis from the nucleus, where the DNA transcribes into messenger RNA (mRNA). mRNA travels to the ribosomes, which translate the code into amino acids, which are the building blocks of proteins.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for the detailed explanation! So, ribosomes are large protein and RNA complexes that are responsible for protein synthesis. They receive instructions from the nucleus and use mRNA to translate these instructions into amino acids, the building blocks of proteins.
Student (to the teacher): Now, could you explain the role of mitochondria in cells? Why are they often referred to as the "powerhouses" of cells?

Teacher (to the student): Mitochondria are often called the powerhouse of the cell because they make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), which is the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. Without mitochondria, no energy can be generated.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, mitochondria are crucial for cells because they produce ATP, the cell's main energy-carrying molecule. Without mitochondria, cells wouldn't be able to generate energy.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how mitochondria use the chemical energy in glucose and other nutrients to make ATP? What is the process of cellular respiration in mitochondria?
Teacher (to the student): Sure. Cellular respiration uses oxygen and produces carbon dioxide as waste. This process is crucial for the production of ATP.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, during cellular respiration, mitochondria use oxygen and produce carbon dioxide as waste, and this process is crucial for the production of ATP.
Student (to the teacher): Now, I'm curious about the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells. Could you explain how it relates to the principle of "form follows function"?

Teacher (to the student): Muscle cells have a very high concentration of mitochondria that produce ATP, since muscles require a lot of energy to keep the body moving. Lactic acid is the result of cells not receiving enough oxygen.

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, muscle cells have a high concentration of mitochondria due to their high energy requirement. This is an example of the "form follows function" principle because the structure (high concentration of mitochondria) is directly related to the function (high energy requirement).
Student (to the teacher): Now, could you tell me about peroxisomes and their functions in cells? How do they contribute to the detoxification process in the body?

Teacher (to the student): Peroxisomes are small, round organelles enclosed by single membranes. They break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. For example, peroxisomes break down and detoxify alcohol in the liver.

Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how peroxisomes break down hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water?

Teacher (to the student): Many oxidation reactions in peroxisomes produce hydrogen peroxide, which can be harmful to cells. However, peroxisomes contain enzymes that break down the hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water, which prevents damage to the cell.

main.text: Nice to meet you! I am Ruffle. I can help you reflect on the material.
Explain the principle of “form follows function”, providing one example of how this principle applies to the structure and organization of eukaryotic cells.
structure should be used related to function
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

The principle of form follows function means that the function of a particular structure is specifically designed to help the structure carry out its particular function. There are many examples where a type of eukaryotic cell is enriched in a particular structure or organelle to optimize its ability to perform a particular function. These include:  (A)	Cells that need to make a lot of proteins, like pancreatic cells that make a high quantity of digestive enzymes, contain many ribosomes, the structure responsible for protein synthesis.  (B) Muscle cells have a very high concentration of mitochondria in order to make high amounts of ATP (the cell’s short-term stored energy) to keep your body moving.
What are ribosomes composed of, where in the cell are they used and what function are they used for? What provides them with the instructions for their function?

they can be found attached to plasma membranes cytoplasmic side of the endoplasmic reticulum side and the nuclear outer membrane.  they get their "orders" for protein synthesis (their function) from the nucleaus where the dna transcribes into the rna.  they are responsible for protein synthesis.
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Each ribosome is composed of two subunits, a large and a small, each of which contains both proteins and RNA. Ribosomes may group as clusters or remain individual ribosomes that freely float in the cytoplasm. Additionally, ribosomes may also attach to the cytoplasmic side of the endoplasmic reticulum or the nuclear envelope’s outer membrane. They are used for linking amino acids together in a particular order to make proteins, using the information within mRNA (which is made using DNA in the nucleus) to direct the identity and order of amino acids in the protein.
How does the act of breathing support cellular respiration in eukaryotic cells, what are the key inputs and outputs of this cellular process and where in the cell does it occur?
i don't know
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

In breathing, the body takes in oxygen during inhalation and releases carbon dioxide during exhalation. This is related to cellular respiration, which uses oxygen to make adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a form of short-term energy storage, and produces carbon dioxide as a byproduct. Thus, breathing provides the oxygen that the body’s cells need for cellular respiration and removes the carbon dioxide they produce as waste. In eukaryotic cells, cellular respiration occurs in the mitochondria.
What is the importance of peroxisomes and how would their absence or reduction affect an organism?
they break down fatty acids and amino acids and detoxify poisons that may enter the body, the body would store toxins without them
Thank you for the response! As a reference, here is our model solution:

Peroxisomes carry out oxidation reactions that break down fatty acids and amino acids. They also detoxify many poisons that may enter the body. (Many of these oxidation reactions release hydrogen peroxide, H2O2, which would be damaging to cells; however, when these reactions are confined to peroxisomes, enzymes safely break down the H2O2 into oxygen and water.) For example, peroxisomes in liver cells detoxify alcohol. Their absence or reduction would lead to death of the organism.

main.text: Teacher (to the student): cell structure is related to its function

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, if I understand correctly, the phrase "form follows function" in cell biology means that the structure of a cell or its components is designed in a way that allows it to perform its specific function.
Student (to the teacher): Could you provide an example to illustrate this concept?
Teacher (to the student): ribosomes synthesize protein
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for the example! So, ribosomes in cells that synthesize large amounts of protein is an example of "form follows function".
Student (to the teacher): Now, could you describe the structure and function of ribosomes in eukaryotic cells?
Teacher (to the student): ribosomes receive orders from the nucleus
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, ribosomes receive “orders” for protein synthesis from the nucleus.
Student (to the teacher): Could you tell me more about the structure of ribosomes and how they contribute to protein synthesis?
Teacher (to the student): mrna travels to ribosomes and translates the code sequence into the order of amino acids. amino acids are the building blocks of proteins

Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, ribosomes are large protein and RNA complexes that receive orders for protein synthesis from the nucleus. mRNA travels to the ribosomes for translation, turning the code sequence into the order of amino acids, which are the building blocks of proteins.
Student (to the teacher): Now, could you explain the role of mitochondria in cells?
Teacher (to the student): mitochondria make atp, the cells main energy molecule
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, the role of mitochondria in cells is to make ATP, the cell’s main energy-carrying molecule.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain why mitochondria are often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells?
Teacher (to the student): it does all the work
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, mitochondria are often referred to as the ''powerhouses'' of cells because they do all the work in terms of energy production.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how mitochondria use chemical energy in glucose and other nutrients to make ATP?
Teacher (to the student): it uses oxygen and produces co2
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, mitochondria use oxygen and produce CO2 in the process of making ATP.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain more about the process of cellular respiration in mitochondria?
Teacher (to the student): they produce lactic acid
Student (to the teacher): I appreciate your response! So, during the process of cellular respiration, mitochondria can produce lactic acid.

Student (to the teacher): However, I'm not sure if this fully explains the process of cellular respiration. Could you provide a bit more detail about how mitochondria convert glucose and other nutrients into ATP?
Teacher (to the student): i dont know
Student (to the teacher): That's okay! I appreciate your honesty. I would be thrilled if you could check it and get back to me.
Student (to the teacher): In the meantime, could you explain how the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells relates to the principle of ''form follows function''?
Teacher (to the student): i already did

Student (to the teacher): I apologize if I missed it. So, the concentration of mitochondria in muscle cells is high due to their high energy requirement, which is an example of the principle "form follows function".
Student (to the teacher): Could you provide more details about why muscle cells have a high concentration of mitochondria?
Teacher (to the student): they need energy to keep moving
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, muscle cells have a high concentration of mitochondria because they need a lot of energy to keep moving.
Student (to the teacher): Now, could you explain what peroxisomes are and what functions they perform in cells?
Teacher (to the student): small organelles enclosed by membranes. they break down fatty acids and amino acids
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your explanation! So, peroxisomes are small organelles enclosed by membranes that carry out oxidation reactions to break down fatty acids and amino acids.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain how peroxisomes contribute to the detoxification process in the body?
Teacher (to the student): enzymes break them down
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, enzymes in peroxisomes break down many poisons, contributing to the detoxification process in the body.
Student (to the teacher): Could you explain more about how peroxisomes break down hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water?
Teacher (to the student): i just did
Student (to the teacher): I apologize if I misunderstood. So, peroxisomes break down hydrogen peroxide into oxygen and water as part of their detoxification function.
Student (to the teacher): Could you provide an example of how peroxisomes function in a specific type of cell, like liver cells?
Teacher (to the student): detoxify alcohol
Student (to the teacher): Thank you for your response! So, peroxisomes in liver cells detoxify alcohol, which is a great example of their function.
Student (to the teacher): I think I've asked all the questions I wanted to learn. Thank you so much for your time and patience!

main.text: Nice to meet you! I am Ruffle. I can help you reflect on the material.
Explain the principle of “form follows function”, providing one example of how this principle applies to the structure and organization of eukaryotic cells.
Basically that however something is designed it should allow the function of the purpose of the item - you shouldn't design needlessly without considering the function
This is a good start! You can take a look at our model solution:

The principle of form follows function means that the function of a particular structure is specifically designed to help the structure carry out its particular function. There are many examples where a type of eukaryotic cell is enriched in a particular structure or organelle to optimize its ability to perform a particular function. These include:  (A)	Cells that need to make a lot of proteins, like pancreatic cells that make a high quantity of digestive enzymes, contain many ribosomes, the structure responsible for protein synthesis.  (B) Muscle cells have a very high concentration of mitochondria in order to make high amounts of ATP (the cell’s short-term stored energy) to keep your body moving.
